ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

******
[2]
Date: Fri 15 Jul 2022
Source: 24 Hours News [in Croatian, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.24sata.hr/news/svake-noci-je-uginulo-izmedu-10-i-12-krava-mojem-bratu-su-se-na-rukama-pojavili-plikovi-848657


After the PU of Sisak-Moslavina [Sisacko-Moslavacka] stated in its press release that 58 cows died while grazing freely in the area of the Lonjsko Polje Nature Park, we spoke with a farmer from Donji Selo near the settlement of Osekovo in the wider area of Popovača.

"One of my 35 cows died 10 days ago. They were grazing freely in Lonjsko Polje on an area of 1500 hectares. Then my brother and I, who also have 35 cows, thought that the cause was clover," 35-year-old [NR] told us. "After that, 2 or 3 days later, 2 cows died, but they did not suspect any infection, but attributed that death to clover. The alarm was raised when cows started dying en masse during the night for the last 3 days.

"Every night, between 10 and 12 cows died in the field, because many farmers besides my brother and I keep cows there. From our village alone, apart from the 2 of us, 15 other owners keep them in Lonjsko Polje. Interestingly, not a single calf or horse that was grazing there died," [NR] tells us, whose 5 cows died and Agroproteinka employees took them away. "In addition to the 5 dead, one cow disappeared, while 3 cows owned by my brother's OPG also died, and 2 were missing." After that, the brothers removed all the cattle from the pasture and divided them into 2 groups that are in isolation where they are for the 5th day until it is determined whether the infection has spread.

While we were talking, the brother, 27, who had blisters on his hands called from the hospital where they confirmed that he was infected with typhoid fever or anthrax.

"My brother and I, when the inspectors came, caught one cow that was suspicious, and now it is obvious that the anthrax has spread to it as well. All of us who were in contact with the cows had to go for an examination to determine if we were also infected by any chance. Unfortunately, he got infected and stayed in the hospital, and luckily, I don't have any symptoms for now," [NR] told us, adding that it is obvious that the brothers came in contact with the saliva of the cow they caught. He said that in addition to saliva, anthrax can be transmitted from person to person through droplets.

The police conducted an investigation in cooperation with the veterinary inspection of the State Inspectorate.

[Byline: Željko Rukavina]

