******
[3]
Date: Sat 16 Jul 2022
Source: Index [in Croatian, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/u-lonjskom-polju-od-antraksa-masovno-ugiba-stoka-cetiri-osobe-zavrsile-u-bolnici/2380408.aspx


The number of dead cattle in the Lonjsko Polje Nature Park is increasing, and according to unofficial information, 107 cattle have died since the beginning of July [2022]. In the meantime, the Ministry of Agriculture announced that the dead cattle from Lonjsko Polje had anthrax.

"The Public Health Institute took samples from the sick patient; today [16 Jul 2022] they are taking samples from these 3 more patients. As of this morning, we have confirmation of anthrax in one cow. This is the confirmation of the analysis carried out by the Croatian Veterinary Institute. We can say that the case is under complete control, there is no room for panic. The Ministry of Agriculture will take all necessary actions related to the sale of livestock and animal products," Inoslav Brkić, head of the Institute of Public Health of the Sisak-Moslavina County, told HRT. All the patients had cutaneous anthrax.

The Ministry of Agriculture announced that in the cattle that died in the area of the Lonjsko Polje Nature Park, smallpox or anthrax was confirmed. The Ministry reported that, considering that a large number of animals died in the area of the Lonjsko polje Pasnjaka Osekovo Nature Park, and the deaths were preceded by the appearance of neurological clinical signs, it ordered the exhumation of the carcasses of the 2 dead animals and the taking of a sample for laboratory diagnostics in order to rule out femur and taking brain samples to rule out rabies and bovine spongiform encephalopathy.

The dissection of the carcasses of dead animals and the laboratory analysis of samples from dead animals were carried out by the Croatian Veterinary Institute in Zagreb. Today [16 Jul 2022], the Ministry received the results of the necropsy, as well as the results of the laboratory tests, which confirmed the death of cattle.

In the joint coordination of the Ministry of Agriculture and the State Inspectorate, further activities and measures are being implemented in the area of the Osekovo pastures, Lonjsko Polje Nature Park, with the aim of preventing the spread and suppression of the infectious disease, according to the press release.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

["Lonjsko Polje (English: Lonja Field) is the largest protected wetland in both Croatia and the entire Danube basin. It covers an area of 505.6 square kilometres (195.2 sq mi), extending along the river Sava from the areas east of Sisak, the lower course of the river Lonja for which it is named, to the areas west of Nova Gradiška, along the course of the river Veliki Strug. The area of Lonjsko Polje is designated a nature park (park prirode), a kind of protected area in Croatia. The institution was established in 1998, and it is based in the village of Jasenovac. According to the criteria of the Birds Directive of the European Union, the park is an important habitat for birds (important birds area: IBA)."
(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonjsko_Polje)

So far we have a confirmation of anthrax in livestock in the park and of a limited number of human cutaneous cases. As to what initiated this severe outbreak we have yet to learn. Based on personal experience, and especially in the Northwest Territory of Canada, I suspect that they have had a long-term experience with anthrax in the area, and that this incident has been exacerbated by a plenitude of blood-feeding Tabanid flies, taking the infection from animal to animal. Anthrax deaths in wildlife can be easily missed, but when private livestock are affected, it gets reported. The latter should have been subjected to routine annual vaccination and the carcasses burnt, if possible, and otherwise buried.

One last word of advice: if you suspect anthrax, do NOT necropsy the carcass. It puts you at severe risk and grossly contaminates a wider area of soil which should be chemically sterilised. Take blood samples or swabs for laboratory confirmation. Swabbing the nasal turbinates is a sound alternative. We have had positive turbinates from skulls out in the sun for 3-4+ years. - Mod.MHJ

